# Configuration: Use GhostConfig

All configuration must use `ghostconfig.GhostConfig`. Never use plain dicts, dataclasses, argparse, or other config systems.

## Pass Sub-configs to Submodules

Slice the config with `[]` and pass the relevant sub-config into each submodule. This keeps each class self-contained — it reads only what it needs and ignores the rest.

```python
# ✅ GOOD — each submodule owns its slice of config
class LitModule(LightningModule):
    def __init__(self, config: GhostConfig):
        self.model = Model(config["model"])
        self.dataset = Dataset(config["dataset"])
        self.learning_rate = config.get("learning_rate", 1e-3)
        config.check()
```

```python
# ❌ BAD — passing the whole config or a plain dict
class LitModule(LightningModule):
    def __init__(self, config: dict):
        self.model = Model(config)         # model sees unrelated keys
        self.learning_rate = config["lr"]  # KeyError instead of a helpful default
```

## Call check() Once, at the Top Level

Only the top-level entry point should call `config.check()`. Submodules just read their slice; the root is responsible for validation.

```python
def train(config_path: str):
    config = GhostConfig.create(config_path)
    module = LitModule(config)
    config.check()   # ← one call, after all submodules have read their keys
```

## Always Provide Defaults via get()

Use `.get(key, default)` for scalar values. The default documents the expected type and serves as a fallback that `check()` will flag as missing.

```python
hidden_size = config.get("hidden_size", 256)   # ✅ self-documenting default
hidden_size = config["hidden_size"]             # ❌ crashes immediately with no helpful message
```
